data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Inventory

| Line | API | Pattern |
|------|-----|---------|
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call | **Blocking call interruption** |
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | Thread.Interrupt | Wake blocked thread (obsolete: `SYSLIB0046`) |
| `_thread.Abort()` | Thread.Abort | Forcible kill (`PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8) |
| `while (true)` | Loop | **Cancellable work loop** |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny unblocks on either a new event OR cancellation
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (index == 1) // cancellation signaled
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string item;
            lock (_lock) { item = _queue.Dequeue(); }
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // wakes RunLoop via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Unblocks on **either** new work or cancellation |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal; no exception injection |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop cooperates with cancellation |

## Pitfalls to Watch

1. **Race between Dequeue and empty queue** — The original code has this bug too: multiple `Set()` calls can coalesce, causing `Dequeue` on an empty queue. Guard with:
   ```csharp
   lock (_lock)
   {
       if (_queue.Count == 0) continue;
       item = _queue.Dequeue();
   }
   ```

2. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** — It's `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks timer/callback handles.

3. **`Thread.Interrupt` is also obsolete** — It's marked `SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9 and was unreliable even in Framework (only works in `WaitSleepJoin` state). Don't use it as a substitute.

4. **Cancellation is not immediate** — If `Handle(item)` runs for a long time, the loop won't check cancellation until it finishes. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `Handle` if it does expensive work.

## Simpler Alternative: `Channel<T>`

For new .NET 8 code, `System.Threading.Channels` replaces the manual queue+event+lock pattern entirely:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _task;

    public void Start()
    {
        _task = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        if (_task is not null)
            await _task;
    }

    public void Dispose() => _cts.Dispose();
}
```

This eliminates the `ManualResetEvent`, explicit `lock`, `Queue`, and `Thread` entirely — all replaced by a single thread-safe `Channel<T>` with built-in async enumeration and cancellation support.
